SCHACHIN (Senum, SHEIN), Alexis.-—A boyar of a distinguished family whose appointment as commander in chief of the army was intended to silence the com— plaints of the Nationalists that too many foreigners were employed in high offices. The quarrel between the Czar and Schachin at a banquet during the period of punishment of the 81161112, page 38 of the Diary‚ ensued not without good reason. When it had become known in the summer of 1698 that the Czar was returning sooner than was generally expected, the surprised boyars held councils twice a day and under threat of the whip forced the merchants’ clerks to make out accounts for them. The promotions of officers made by Schachin during the Czar's absence were all cancelled.
